messages.text: As a class we will check in in the mornings, and also, will be proactive about messaging when we need (or even just want for funzies) review
<@U4RKZ1A94> also really likes doing review towards the end of the day.
<@U4YB9LF2N> and others like maybe in the mornings, when we check in about what students will need to deliver, we can review as is appropriate to make sure students are ready.
<@U4WK6BJQM> also proposes we should be  very clear when something is not so pivotal.
<@U3Z1PUBB2> and <@U4M2ULFUK> agree that the avoidance of big topics in small periods of time is good.
<@U4M2ULFUK> suggests rescheduling when possible to wrap up a single given topic before moving on to another.
<@U3Z1PUBB2> proposes that anytime we might be covering materials outside the main arc, that explicit time is taken to explain the importance and why we must cover it "outside of context".
<@U4YB9LF2N> really likes the flow of covering a material in a lesson and then the next day being asked to implement it in exercises.

<@U3R672XGQ> really likes a good theme and finds the multitude of topics to be counter to this preference. In particular he did not have a good explanation for why the SSR was relevant and only experienced it by researching by the skin of his teeth. Docker and AWS exasperated this.
<@U2PSX14KF> wrt the templating exercise didn't really mind the small exposure.
<@U4YB9LF2N> has a preference for mastery of only a few topics vs a survey of many.

<@U4RKZ1A94> had a meaningful experience where 2 large topics (supertest and handlebars) were only given a very small and fixed period of time, where it would have been preferable to be able to spend more time on them (to learn from colleagues etc.), also, this led to an experience of not enough time to consolidate.
<@U4WK6BJQM> feels most pertinently the trade off between a variety of topics and the ability to review/consolidate
Knex seeds and migrations
Formal code reviews on smaller projects
Formal review sessions
The variety of topics covered in a given day/week

messages.text: <@U2PSX14KF> also points out some external support to really take lunch might be beneficial.
The overwhelming sentiment is that the morning, while rested and caffeinated, is best used for coding stuff
<@U4NBAUKD4> likes the idea of a trxxsition back into coding exercise post career services.

<@U3R672XGQ> seconds <@U4M2ULFUK>'s sentiment of a feeling of coding interruption. On the one hand post lunch is already drowzy and he likes the flow, and a hard stop at 3:30 might crete some deadline anxiety. He also like the idea of morning space.
<@U4M2ULFUK> feels like the current configuration feels like too much of a solid block without coding, and proposes perhaps the morning.
<@U2PSX14KF> (and he is surely not alone) always feels like is is an interruption.

<@U4RKZ1A94> finds the lunch and early afternoon time precious and sometimes finds that the later, and more challenging time should be left for CS.

Also it turns out that the transition back into coding is maybe rougher than it might need to be.
<@U3Z1PUBB2> likes having a come back together moment after lunch and also having them all hacking at closing time
Career Services Hacking Timing
<@U3Z1PUBB2> is always delighted at how industrious the class is.
We will look to do more formal pairing assignments, especially among people who not usually sitting next to each other
As a reminder, students can work all throughout the space. Leaving the space is off limits, as we need the ability to come together in the same room at short notice for a variety of reasons.
Some students really appreciated the benefits of being close by each other, to facilitate collaboration
We talked about going out to the lab. Some students felt like out of consideration they ought not to bother the 42ers
Working out of other parts of the space than our classroom
This week all was gravy
